Liberal Democrat Councillor for Saddleworth North Ward on Oldham Council Learn more
by Garth Harkness on 15 June, 2015
Lib Dem Councillors Rod Blyth, Garth Harkness and Diane Williamson have written on behalf of the Oldham Liberal Democrat council Group to Prime Minister David Cameron demanding action on food poverty, particularly to address the increasing prevalence of children attending school hungry.
In their letter the Councillors state that “access good food is a basic human right” and condemn the fact that “in Britain today many of our citizens are struggling to afford to provide an adequate, nutritious diet for themselves and their families”.
The Councillors have proposed a concrete plan of action to the Prime Minister to:
· Establish an official definition of food poverty. Government already has a definition of fuel poverty, and we believe that this should be possible for food poverty. By establishing a definition, it will be possible to monitor it and establish progress in eliminating it;
· Reduce poverty by enhancing the national minimum wage and by reducing the burden of taxation on low-income working families, to speed up payments made to claimants, and to ensure that benefits are sufficient to provide them with an adequate and nutritious diet;
· Safeguard programmes such as Healthy Start Vouchers, Free School Meals and Meals on Wheels and to extend these to reach all who are eligible;
· Support the establishment of breakfast clubs in all schools where there is a need;
· Support school holiday food provision in deprived communities to combat the increasing occurrence of hunger amongst poor families when free school meals are unavailable;
· Increase the amount of surplus food redistributed through Fare Share and similar organisations to support the commendable efforts of local food banks and other community-based food agencies providing food parcels or hot meals to those in need. At present 98% of this food goes to landfill or is burned.
· Establish one of twelve pilot projects proposed by the All-Party Parliamentary Inquiry into Food in Oldham. These pilots would draw together private, voluntary and public expertise to test the ‘Feeding Britain’ approach identified by the inquiry. Oldham has several extremely deprived electoral wards that would benefit from being a pilot area.
Food poverty is an important issue for Oldham’s Liberal Democrats. As the Councillors stated to the Prime Minister “if you commit your Government to take the action that we outline in this letter that we will do all that we can to support you in making food poverty in Britain a thing of the past”.
